# crucible daemon configuration.
#
# CRUCIBLE_FLAGS is passed verbatim to `crucible daemon` (systemd splits
# it on whitespace, so keep it on a single line). Edit the paths for your
# host, then apply with:
#
#   sudo systemctl restart crucible
#
# Run `crucible daemon --help` for the full flag list. Common flags:
#   --firecracker-bin PATH   firecracker binary            (required)
#   --kernel PATH            uncompressed vmlinux           (required)
#   --rootfs PATH            default guest rootfs image     (required)
#   --jailer-bin PATH        enables snapshot/fork + jailer isolation
#   --chroot-base DIR        parent of per-VM jailer chroots (default /srv/jailer).
#                            MUST allow device nodes: the jailer mknod's /dev/kvm
#                            here, so a nodev mount (e.g. tmpfs /tmp) makes it inert
#                            ("creating KVM object: Permission denied"). /srv/jailer
#                            on the root fs is safe.
#   --jail-gid GID           gid the jailer drops firecracker to (default: the kvm
#                            group, so it can open /dev/kvm). Override only to a gid
#                            that also has KVM access.
#   --rootfs-dir DIR         directory of <profile>.ext4 images
#   --work-base DIR          per-sandbox workdirs + durable registry (keep this
#                            OFF /tmp for a service — the registry must survive reboot)
#   --image-dir DIR          converted OCI image cache. REQUIRED to boot images
#                            (`crucible run <image>`, `sandbox create --image`,
#                            `crucible build`); empty — the flag's default —
#                            disables the /images API. Must live OUTSIDE
#                            --work-base. Needs e2fsprogs on the host
#                            (mkfs.ext4 / fsck.ext4 / debugfs), plus resize2fs
#                            for `--disk`.
#   --log-dir DIR            durable per-sandbox logs — `crucible logs` (service
#                            output + exec activity). Defaults to
#                            /var/lib/crucible/logs; empty disables it.
#   --app-db PATH            bbolt store of durable-app desired state — enables
#                            `crucible app` + /apps + the reconcile loop that
#                            re-creates an app's instance after a daemon restart.
#                            Defaults to /var/lib/crucible/apps.db; empty disables
#                            apps. Must live OUTSIDE --work-base.
#   --listen HOST:PORT       API listen address (default 127.0.0.1:7878)
#   --network-egress-iface   host NIC for sandbox egress. Required for sandbox
#                            networking AND for host port publish (`run -p`).
#   --token-file PATH        bearer-key store (default /var/lib/crucible/tokens.json);
#                            add keys with `crucible daemon token add`. Auth turns on
#                            once a key exists. To expose a non-loopback --listen you
#                            MUST set keys and --tls-cert/--tls-key.
#   --tls-cert / --tls-key   PEM cert+key; required to bind a non-loopback address
#   --registry-store PATH    credential store for private-registry pulls
#                            (default /var/lib/crucible/registry.json); add creds
#                            with `crucible registry login`. Empty disables it
#                            (pulls stay anonymous). Holds usable secrets — 0600,
#                            NOT encrypted at rest.
#   --proxy-listen ADDR      ingress proxy HTTP address (e.g. :80): reach an app by
#                            name (<app>.<proxy-domain>) instead of publishing a
#                            host port. Off by default. Pair with --proxy-domain
#                            <domain> and, for HTTPS, --proxy-tls-listen :443 (SNI
#                            passthrough — the guest terminates its own TLS).
#                            Needs --app-db. The daemon runs as root, so it binds
#                            :80/:443 without extra capabilities. See docs/proxy.md.

CRUCIBLE_FLAGS="--firecracker-bin /usr/local/bin/firecracker --kernel /var/lib/crucible/vmlinux --rootfs /var/lib/crucible/rootfs.ext4 --jailer-bin /usr/local/bin/jailer --rootfs-dir /var/lib/crucible/profiles --work-base /var/lib/crucible/run --image-dir /var/lib/crucible/images --app-db /var/lib/crucible/apps.db --registry-store /var/lib/crucible/registry.json --listen 127.0.0.1:7878 --log-format json"

# Add --network-egress-iface <nic> (e.g. eth0) above to enable sandbox
# networking and `crucible run -p HOST:GUEST` port publish. Find yours with:
#   ip -4 route show default | awk '{print $5; exit}'

# Reach apps by name: add --proxy-listen :7879 --proxy-domain apps.local above,
# point DNS/hosts for *.apps.local at this host, then
# `crucible app create web --image … --port 80` is reachable at
# http://web.apps.local:7879/ with no host port published. See docs/proxy.md.
# install.sh seeds :7879 by default — next to the 7878 API and out of the common
# publish range (:80/:8080/:3000/…), so it never contends with an app you run via
# `-p`/`-P`. For a production ingress on the standard port use --proxy-listen :80
# (root binds it without extra caps) — then it's just http://web.apps.local/.
# TLS SNI passthrough is opt-in (needs a TLS-serving guest): add
# --proxy-tls-listen :7880 (or :443). host:port pins an interface
# (127.0.0.1:7879 = loopback only).
